    <h1>Re-Engagement Campaign</h1>
    <p class="description">An email sequence designed to win back subscribers who've stopped opening or clicking your messages. Email lists decay by <strong>22% annually</strong> — a quarterly re-engagement campaign recovers 5-15% of dormant contacts and removes the rest before they damage your sender reputation.</p>
    <div class="post-meta">
      <div class="meta-author">
        <div class="meta-avatar">AVR</div>
        <div class="meta-author-info">
          <span class="meta-author-name"><a href="/authors/akshay-vr/">Akshay VR</a></span>
          <span class="meta-author-role">Marketing Head · theStacc</span>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="meta-divider"></div>
      <div class="meta-item"><span class="meta-label">Published</span><span class="meta-value">Jul 2026</span></div>
      <div class="meta-divider"></div>
      <div class="meta-item"><span class="meta-label">Read</span><span class="meta-value">6 min</span></div>
      <div class="meta-divider"></div>
      <div class="meta-item"><span class="meta-label">Also called</span><span class="meta-value">Win-back campaign, list reactivation</span></div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="post-body-wrap">
    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p>A <strong>re-engagement campaign</strong> is an email sequence of 2-3 messages sent to subscribers who haven't opened or clicked your emails in 90-180 days. The goal is to recover the 5-15% who will re-engage with the right prompt, then permanently remove the rest — protecting your sender reputation, reducing list costs, and restoring accurate open and click metrics.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Sequence length</div>
            <div class="tms-value">2-3 emails</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Email Marketing</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Expected recovery</div>
            <div class="tms-value">5-15% of dormant</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Intermediate</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Every email list has a decay problem. According to HubSpot data, approximately 22% of subscribers go dormant every year — they stop opening, stop clicking, and become dead weight on your list. The typical response is to keep sending and hope they come back. The correct response is a structured re-engagement campaign: make one clear attempt to win them back, then cut them if they don't respond. It's the list hygiene practice that keeps email a profitable channel.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is a re-engagement campaign?</h2>
        <p>A re-engagement campaign is a targeted email sequence sent exclusively to your inactive segment. "Inactive" typically means no opens or clicks in 90 days, 6 months, or after 5-10 consecutive campaigns — depending on your sending frequency and list characteristics.</p>
        <p>The campaign has three stages:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Define inactive.</strong> Segment your list by last engagement date. Pull everyone who meets your inactivity threshold into a separate segment.</li>
          <li><strong>Send the sequence.</strong> 2-3 emails over 1-2 weeks, escalating urgency with each message.</li>
          <li><strong>Make the decision.</strong> Anyone who opens, clicks, or confirms stays active. Anyone who doesn't gets removed or suppressed.</li>
        </ol>
        <p>The key insight is that re-engagement campaigns are not primarily about recovering lost subscribers — they're about removing subscribers who should be removed before their inactivity damages your deliverability for everyone else.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Why inactive subscribers are dangerous, not just inactive</div>
          <p>Internet Service Providers (Gmail, Outlook, Yahoo) track engagement rates across your entire sending domain. High proportions of unopened mail from your domain are a spam signal — even if individual subscribers never marked you as spam. Sending to a list that's 30% inactive degrades deliverability for your 70% who want your emails. Re-engagement campaigns protect the active majority by removing the inactive minority.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why re-engagement campaigns matter for email performance</h2>
        <p>The business case for re-engagement campaigns sits in four places:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Sender reputation protection.</strong> ISPs track engagement rates at the domain level. A sustained pattern of low engagement on your sending domain lowers your sender score, which affects inbox placement for all your emails — including campaigns to engaged subscribers.</li>
          <li><strong>Deliverability improvement.</strong> Most email platforms rate your "deliverability score" based on open rates, bounce rates, and spam complaint rates. Inactive subscribers pull down your open rate average, dragging your deliverability metrics toward the threshold where emails start landing in spam.</li>
          <li><strong>Cost reduction.</strong> Almost every email platform charges by list size or sends per month. An inactive segment of 10,000 subscribers at $0.001 per send costs $10 per campaign — for zero engagement. At 26 campaigns per year, that's $260 wasted. For larger lists, re-engagement campaigns pay for themselves in reduced platform costs.</li>
          <li><strong>Accurate metrics.</strong> Open rates and click rates calculated against a bloated inactive list are meaningless. A 16% open rate on a clean list tells you something. A 16% open rate on a list that's 40% inactive tells you that your actual engagement rate among people who are paying attention is around 27%.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How to run a re-engagement campaign</h2>

        <h3>Step 1 — Define your inactive segment</h3>
        <p>Choose your inactivity threshold and segment accordingly:</p>

        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># Common inactivity thresholds</span><br>
          <span class="uf-label">Daily sender:</span> <span class="uf-new">90 days</span> no opens/clicks<br>
          <span class="uf-label">Weekly sender:</span> <span class="uf-new">120-180 days</span> no opens/clicks<br>
          <span class="uf-label">Monthly sender:</span> <span class="uf-new">6-12 months</span> no opens/clicks<br>
          <span class="uf-label">Volume-based:</span> <span class="uf-new">10+ campaigns</span> without any interaction
        </div>

        <h3>Step 2 — Write the 3-email sequence</h3>
        <p>The standard re-engagement sequence escalates in urgency:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Email 1 — "We miss you"</strong>: Warm and low-pressure. Remind them what they signed up for. Offer a reason to return. Subject: "Still interested in [value prop]?"</li>
          <li><strong>Email 2 — "Last chance" with incentive</strong>: Introduce a specific reason to click now. B2C: discount or exclusive offer. B2B: a high-value resource or insight. Subject: "A gift for you — but only if you want it."</li>
          <li><strong>Email 3 — "We're removing you"</strong>: This email consistently gets the highest open rates of the three. The subject line alone drives re-engagement: "Removing you from our list on [date]." One-click confirmation button. No response = removal.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Step 3 — Act on the results</h3>
        <p>Anyone who opens, clicks, or confirms re-engages returns to your active segment. Everyone else gets suppressed or deleted within 48 hours of the campaign end date.</p>

        <h2 id="types">Re-engagement approach by audience type</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Audience type</th><th>Best incentive</th><th>Sequence tone</th><th>Expected re-engagement rate</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr class="row-highlight"><td><strong>E-commerce (B2C)</strong></td><td>Discount, exclusive offer, free shipping</td><td>Warm and promotional</td><td>10-18%</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>B2B SaaS</strong></td><td>Useful content, product update, case study</td><td>Professional, value-first</td><td>8-14%</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Newsletter / Content</strong></td><td>Best-of archive, new series announcement</td><td>Personal, reminder of value</td><td>5-12%</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Professional services</strong></td><td>Industry insight, free consultation</td><td>Advisory, not promotional</td><td>6-10%</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real re-engagement campaign examples</h2>

        <h3>Example 1 — E-commerce clothing retailer</h3>
        <p>A clothing retailer identified 8,000 inactive subscribers who hadn't opened an email in 120 days. They sent a 3-email sequence over 10 days: "We miss you" on day 1, "Here's 15% off for coming back" on day 4, and "We're removing you on Friday" on day 8. Result: 12% re-engagement rate (960 subscribers returned to active), list reduced by 7,040 inactive contacts. Overall list open rate improved from 16% to 24% in the following month's campaigns.</p>

        <h3>Example 2 — B2B marketing agency newsletter</h3>
        <p>A marketing agency noticed 30% of their newsletter list hadn't clicked anything in 6 months. Rather than offering a discount, they sent valuable industry research in the re-engagement sequence — no promotional ask, just useful content. Result: 18% re-engagement rate. The agency attributed the above-average rate to sending content rather than a promotional offer — matching what originally motivated subscribers to sign up.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Re-engagement campaign vs list cleaning — when to do each</h2>
        <p>Re-engagement campaigns and list cleaning are related but different practices. Understanding when to use each prevents doing unnecessary work.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Re-engagement campaign</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Gives inactive subscribers a last chance to stay</li>
              <li>Recovers 5-15% who were just not paying attention</li>
              <li>Creates a clear "removal date" that drives urgency</li>
              <li>Run every 3-6 months as a list health practice</li>
              <li>Requires 2-3 email setup and a segmentation workflow</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>List cleaning (hard removal)</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Immediate removal of bounced and spam-complaint addresses</li>
              <li>No recovery attempt — straight deletion</li>
              <li>For hard bounces and spam complaints only</li>
              <li>Should happen automatically after every campaign</li>
              <li>Requires bounce and complaint tracking, not a campaign</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">6 best practices for re-engagement campaigns</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Define "inactive" clearly before you start.</strong> Make the inactivity threshold consistent across campaigns so your segments are comparable over time. Changing the definition between runs makes it impossible to measure improvement.</li>
          <li><strong>Send the "we're removing you" email.</strong> Teams often skip email 3 because it feels rude. Don't — it consistently generates the highest open rates and re-engagement of the entire sequence. The clarity of a removal deadline produces action.</li>
          <li><strong>Match the re-engagement incentive to what attracted them.</strong> A subscriber who joined for industry insights will not re-engage for a 15% discount. A subscriber who joined for a product discount will not re-engage for a thought leadership article. Review your opt-in offer when writing the incentive email.</li>
          <li><strong>Suppress, don't just delete, when possible.</strong> Suppressing keeps the address in a do-not-send list, preventing it from re-entering your active list through a future opt-in form submission. Deleting allows re-subscription without the inactivity context.</li>
          <li><strong>Exclude re-engagement segments from regular campaigns.</strong> During the re-engagement sequence, remove that segment from your regular campaign sends. Mixing re-engagement with promotional emails confuses the signal and dilutes the urgency of the removal message.</li>
          <li><strong>Run quarterly for fast-growing lists.</strong> If you're adding 500+ subscribers per month, quarterly re-engagement is necessary to prevent the inactive proportion from growing to a deliverability-damaging size. Slower-growing lists can run biannually.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — delaying removal past the deadline</div>
          <p>If your email 3 says "we're removing you on Friday," remove them on Friday. Sending further campaigns after the stated removal date destroys the credibility of the sequence for anyone who notices — and more importantly, delays the deliverability improvements that come from removing inactive contacts. Set the removal workflow to trigger automatically on the stated date.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common re-engagement campaign mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Running it too infrequently</strong> — annual re-engagement campaigns can't keep pace with 22% annual list decay. By the time you run one, the inactive segment may represent 30-40% of your total list.</li>
          <li><strong>Making the emails too promotional</strong> — re-engagement is about demonstrating value, not selling. Promotional re-engagement emails perform worse than value-first approaches for most list types.</li>
          <li><strong>Not segmenting properly first</strong> — sending re-engagement emails to your entire active list irritates engaged subscribers. The sequence must go to inactive contacts only.</li>
          <li><strong>Treating re-engagement rate as the success metric</strong> — the real success metric is overall list health: open rate improvement, deliverability score, and reduced platform cost. A 5% re-engagement rate with a 20% open rate improvement is a better outcome than 15% re-engagement with no deliverability change.</li>
          <li><strong>Using the same subject lines as regular campaigns</strong> — re-engagement subject lines need to stand out from your normal email patterns. Urgency-based, curiosity-based, or honest subjects ("We haven't heard from you in a while") outperform regular promotional subjects in re-engagement contexts.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">How often should I run re-engagement campaigns?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Every 3-6 months. Quarterly for fast-growing lists where new subscribers can go dormant quickly. Biannually for slower-growth lists. The cadence should match how fast your list decays — HubSpot data shows email lists decay by roughly 22% annually, which means quarterly intervention is the default recommendation.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">What is a good re-engagement rate?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Expect 5-15% of inactive subscribers to re-engage. This sounds low, but the value is dual: the 5-15% who return are warm contacts you keep, and the 85-95% who don't respond are safely removed — improving open rates, deliverability, and sender score for everyone else on your list.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Should I offer a discount in re-engagement emails?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>B2C lists respond well to discounts or exclusive offers. B2B lists typically respond better to valuable content — a useful guide, industry report, or insight relevant to their role. Match the incentive to what originally attracted the subscriber to your list.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">What happens to subscribers who don't re-engage?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Remove or suppress them. Suppression means you keep their data but stop sending — useful if you want to preserve analytics or may re-permission them later. Deletion is cleaner but permanent. Either way, stop sending marketing emails to non-responders — continuing to email them damages deliverability for your entire list.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">How do I define 'inactive' for a re-engagement campaign?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Common thresholds: no opens or clicks in 90 days (aggressive), 6 months (standard), or 5-10 consecutive campaigns without interaction (volume-based). Choose the threshold that matches your sending frequency. If you send daily, 90 days is appropriate. If you send monthly, 6 months may be more suitable.</p></div></div>
          </div>
        </div>

